<span id="freeTextContainer15268957247092044203">I was in our local book store buying my current obsession, Dark Places, &amp; as always I had my 1 &amp; 2 year old daughters w me. The deal always is if Nina (our oldest) behaves she gets to pick a book, she loves books so she always behaves in books stores. The children&apos;s section has 4 shelves w recommended books on them, each table done by age group. We hit the birth-3 years table &amp; she picked a colorful book w a little girl on the potty on the cover. I then saw her wandering &amp; we found the &quot;classic </span>
  <span id="freeText15268957247092044203" style="display:none">I was in our local book store buying my current obsession, Dark Places, &amp; as always I had my 1 &amp; 2 year old daughters w me. The deal always is if Nina (our oldest) behaves she gets to pick a book, she loves books so she always behaves in books stores. The children's section has 4 shelves w recommended books on them, each table done by age group. We hit the birth-3 years table &amp; she picked a colorful book w a little girl on the potty on the cover. I then saw her wandering &amp; we found the "classic children's section" which interested me. I let Nina look thru the selections while I tended to my whining 12 month old, Giulia &amp; then w a tap on my thigh &amp; a "pweeze mommy" I turned to see Nina holding a book she had chosen &amp; I was frozen with nostalgia. <br /><br />The Little House was my FAVORITE book as a child! I remember my big sister, she's 13 years older than me, reading me this story constantly. It was always both of our choices. Our copy was worn beyond belief. The pages were faded with some rips, the hard cover had a tiny tear at the bottom corner &amp; the binding was coming apart. You had to be careful not to have the pages fall out. Of all the books in the entire children's section Nina chose this one book. It was like she knew it was a favorite of both her Aunt &amp; myself. I couldn't wait to get the book home &amp; read it to both of our girls! <br /><br />The old country house that is threatened by the big city, but then saved &amp; relocated back to the country where it belongs is a tale. It was written in the '40s, but hold very true today. Nina adores this book as much I my sister did in the early 70s, &amp; I did in the early 80s. With all the technology, iPads, computers &amp; video games children have today, many kids aren't read to. This a a book parents should read to their kids, their is a beautiful lesson hidden in this story, that sometimes the new &amp; improved isn't always better. </span>
