        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer754855936" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer8200349788494108551">So far, with the books I&apos;ve been reading for this challenge, I&apos;ve been able to see why they were selected for the list - the appeal they would have to children. Even if I personally wouldn&apos;t have liked them - as with Each Peach Pear Plum - I can see the appeal to other children.<br/><br/>This is the first book I&apos;ve read where I&apos;ve simply not seen the attraction. I can see how adults would like it - it can be seen as a fable illustrating the negative effects of urbanisation, and has a nice nostalgic elemen</span>
  <span id="freeText8200349788494108551" style="display:none">So far, with the books I've been reading for this challenge, I've been able to see why they were selected for the list - the appeal they would have to children. Even if I personally wouldn't have liked them - as with Each Peach Pear Plum - I can see the appeal to other children.<br /><br />This is the first book I've read where I've simply not seen the attraction. I can see how adults would like it - it can be seen as a fable illustrating the negative effects of urbanisation, and has a nice nostalgic element of returning to, and appreciating, simple living in the countryside.<br /><br />But this is a nostalgia for adults - not for little kids! Kids don't have this perspective. Exposing them to it through a picture book might be seen as important by adults, but I can't really see little kids getting much from this story. Would kids really be interested in the perspective of a house - a house that doesn't do anything, but just sits and watches a city being built around it?<br /><br />Maybe they would - after all, this book won the 1943 Caldecott Medal (but then, are these medals always selected based on children's preferences, or what the adults think is good for children?) and was even made into a short Disney movie (although surely if it had been popular people would still be watching this Disney movie now!). Clearly I'm feeling rather negatively inclined towards the book! The pictures were okay, but nothing amazing (from my perspective, at least - and I'd say I'm in close contact with my inner child!).</span>
  <a data-text-id="8200349788494108551" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
