        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer894354365" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer18336142867338032676">This is one of those books that embeds itself in your memory forever. I read it once or twice as a child at the library but never saw it again after that until I spotted it at a bookstore last year and just had to buy my own copy. It is a simple story about a well-loved house that survives generations and generations, first being built in the country and observing simple life and season changes around it. Over time a town pops up, which later turns into a city, which later turns into a dirty, ov</span>
  <span id="freeText18336142867338032676" style="display:none">This is one of those books that embeds itself in your memory forever. I read it once or twice as a child at the library but never saw it again after that until I spotted it at a bookstore last year and just had to buy my own copy. It is a simple story about a well-loved house that survives generations and generations, first being built in the country and observing simple life and season changes around it. Over time a town pops up, which later turns into a city, which later turns into a dirty, over-populated metropolis. The little house, which was once set peacefully in the country to be loved by a quiet family, is now crowded in a dirty city, squished on all sides by tenements with a light rail buzzing overhead. The house is abandoned, with broken windows and a boarded-up door, until a great-great-granddaughter of the original owner sees the house and compassionately moves it out of the city to the country, where it can be happy again.<br /><br />This is picture book because of its predictable structure. The author offers the reader many clues about what may happen next.<br /><br />The Little House could be integrated into the classroom through a social studies unit on how life and land change over time. It could also be used with younger elementary students who are struggling to comprehend the complex and abstract concept of death, as it displays life cycles in light of a happy ending of redemption.<br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="18336142867338032676" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


